{{LGBT rights}}
The '''Employment Non-Discrimination Act''' ('''ENDA''') is legislation proposed in the [[United States Congress]] that would prohibit [[discrimination]] in hiring and employment on the basis of [[sexual orientation]] or [[gender identity]] by employers with at least 15 employees.

ENDA has been introduced in every Congress since 1994 except the [[109th United States Congress|109th]]. Similar legislation has been introduced without passage since 1974.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nondiscrimination legislation historical timeline|url=http://www.thetaskforce.org/issues/nondiscrimination/timeline|publisher=National Gay and Lesbian Task Force|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524062405/http://www.thetaskforce.org/issues/nondiscrimination/timeline|archive-date=May 24, 2014|accessdate=June 17, 2017|dead-url=yes}}</ref> The bill gained its best chance at passing after the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] gained the majority after [[Republican Revolution|twelve years]] of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] majorities in the [[United States elections, 2006|2006 midterm elections.]] In 2007, [[gender identity]] protections were added to the legislation for the first time. Some sponsors believed that even with a Democratic majority, ENDA did not have enough votes to pass the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] with [[transgender]] inclusion and dropped it from the bill, which passed the House and then died in the Senate. President [[George W. Bush]] threatened to veto the measure. LGBT advocacy organizations and the LGBT community were divided over support of the modified bill.

In 2009, following Democratic gains in the [[United States elections, 2008|2008 elections]], and after the divisiveness of the 2007 debate, Rep. [[Barney Frank]] introduced a transgender-inclusive version of ENDA. He introduced it again in 2011, and Sen. [[Jeff Merkley]] introduced it in the Senate. On November 7, 2013, Merkley's bill passed the Senate with bipartisan support by a vote of 64–32. President [[Barack Obama]] supported the bill's passage.

==Evidence of employment discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation and gender identity==
{{Main|LGBT employment discrimination in the United States}}
In states that have anti-discrimination policies in place, LGBT complaints are equivalent to the number of complaints filed based on sex and fewer than the number of complaints filed based on race.<ref>{{cite web|title=The State of the Workplace: for Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender Americans|url=http://www.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/HRC_Foundation_State_of_the_Workplace_2007-2008.pdf|publisher=Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>Evidence Discrimination based on sexual orientation occurs at a similar rate as sex and race at 4.7 per 10,000, as compared to discrimination based on sex at 5.4 and race at 6.5.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Christopher|title=Evidence of Employment Discrimination on the Basis of Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity: Complaints Filed with State Enforcement Agencies, 1999–2007|url=http://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/Badgett-Sears-Ramos-Emply-Discrim-1999-2007-Nov-08.pdf|publisher=The Williams Institute|accessdate=December 16, 2013}}</ref>

The [[Williams Institute]] estimates the number of LGBT employees as follows: 7 million private sector employees, 1 million state and local employees, and 200,000 employees of the federal government. Thirty percent of state and local LGBT employees live in California and New York. In comparison, less than half of one half of one percent of LGBT state and local employees live in Montana, North Dakota and Wyoming combined.<ref>{{cite web|title=Estimates of LGBT Public Employees|url=http://www.escholarship.org/uc/item/6cz123ww?display=all|publisher=The Williams Institute|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref> As one might expect, many of the documented complaints of discrimination by state and local governments against LGBT employees are in California and New York. Surveys that seek to document discrimination on the basis of perceived sexual orientation and/or gender identity are often conducted with a pool of self identified LGBT people, making it difficult to ascertain the impact of this type of discrimination on non-LGBT individuals.

One source of evidence for hiring discrimination against openly gay men comes from a field experiment that sent two fictitious but realistic resumes to roughly 1,700 entry-level job openings. The two resumes were very similar in terms of the applicant's qualifications, but one resume for each opening mentioned that the applicant had been part of a gay organization in college. The results showed that applicants without the gay signal had an 11.5 percent chance of being called for an interview; openly gay applicants had only a 7.2 percent chance. The callback gap varied widely according to the location of the job. Most of the overall gap detected in the study was driven by the Southern and Midwestern states in the sample – Texas, Florida, and Ohio. The Western and Northeastern states in the sample (California, Nevada, Pennsylvania, and New York) had only small and statistically insignificant callback gaps.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1086/661653 Tilcsik, A. (2011). Pride and prejudice: Employment discrimination against openly gay men in the United States. American Journal of Sociology, 117, 586–626.]</ref>

Transgender people may experience higher rates of discrimination than the LGBT population. A survey of transgender and gender non-conforming people conducted by the [[National Center for Transgender Equality]] found 90 percent of respondents experienced harassment, mistreatment, or discrimination on the job or took actions like hiding who they are to avoid it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grant |first=Jamie M. |title=Injustice at Every Turn: A Report of the National Transgender Discrimination Survey. |url=http://www.thetaskforce.org/reports_and_research/ntds |publisher=National Center for Transgender Equality and National Gay and Lesbian Task Force |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006061544/http://www.thetaskforce.org/reports_and_research/ntds |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |df= }}</ref> In comparison, a review of studies conducted by the Williams Institute in 2007 found that transgender people experienced employment discrimination at a rate 15 to 57 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Badgette|first=M.V. Lee|url=http://www3.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/publications/Bias%20in%20the%20Workplace.pdf|title=Bias in the Workplace: Consistent Evidence of Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity Discrimination|publisher=The Williams Institute|accessdate=December 16, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073606/http://www3.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/publications/Bias%20in%20the%20Workplace.pdf|archivedate=July 20, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

In a survey conducted by Harris Interactive, 38 percent of LGBT people report incomes less than $35,000, compared to 33 percent of all U.S. adults over age 18.<ref>{{cite web|last=Witeck|first=Bob|title=Ending Employment Discrimination in America: Lies, Damned Lies and Statistics About America's LGBT Families|url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/gaysouthflorida/2009/11/ending-employment-discrimination-in-america-lies-damned-lies-and-statistics-about-americas-lgbt-families.html|accessdate=December 16, 2013}}</ref>

==Provisions==
The current version of the bill under consideration in Congress prohibits private employers with more than 15 employees from discriminating on the basis of sexual orientation or gender identity. Religious organizations are provided an exception, broader than that found in the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref name=HuffPo>{{cite news|last1=Bendery|first1=Jennifer|title=Gay Rights Groups Pull Support For ENDA Over Sweeping Religious Exemption|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/08/enda-religious-exemption_n_5568736.html|accessdate=16 August 2014|date=8 July 2014}}</ref> Non-profit membership-only clubs, except labor unions, are similarly exempt.

All versions of the bill, irrespective of the military's changing policies with respect to service by open gays and lesbians, have provided an exclusion for the military as an employer of members of the armed forces, though not as an employer of civilians.<ref>103rd Congress: "For purposes of this Act, the term 'employment or employment opportunities' does not apply to the relationship between the United States and members of the Armed Forces."; 112th Congress: "In this Act, the term 'employment' does not apply to the relationship between the United States and members of the Armed Forces."</ref>

Since the 111th Congress, the legislation has included language to prevent any reading of the law as a modification of the federal definition of marriage established in the Defense of Marriage Act (1995).<ref>111th and 112th Congresses: "In this Act, the term 'married' refers to marriage as such term is defined in section 7 of title 1, United States Code (commonly known as the 'Defense of Marriage Act')."</ref> Since the 110th Congress, a related provision aimed at non-marital legal relations like civil unions and domestic partnerships prevents requiring an employer to treat unmarried and married couples similarly.<ref>112th Congress: "Nothing in this Act shall be construed to require a covered entity to treat an unmarried couple in the same manner as the covered entity treats a married couple for purposes of employee benefits."</ref>

==Legislative activity==

[[File:S 2056 - Employment Nondiscrimination Act of 1996 - Senate vote.svg|thumb|400px|right|Senate vote on '''Employment Nondiscrimination Act of 1996'''.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/bill/votes/7760#.UWKgfFezf78 S 2056 – Employment Nondiscrimination Act of 1996 – Voting Record]</ref>
{{legend|#000080|Both yes}}
{{legend|#0066FF|One yes, one didn't vote}}
{{legend|#D42AFF|One yes, one no}}
{{legend|#800000|Both no}}]]

On May 14, 1974, the fifth anniversary of the [[Stonewall Rebellion]], Reps. [[Bella Abzug]] (D-NY) and [[Ed Koch]] (D-NY) introduced {{USBill|93|H.R.|14752}}, the "[[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]]", which would have added sexual orientation and gender identity to the protected classes specified in the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]], thus prohibiting discrimination in employment and access to public accommodations and facilities.<ref>(October 13, 2007) [http://www.stonewallvets.org/BellaAbzug.htm U.S. Congressmember Bella S. Abzug] Stonewall.org. Accessed October 20, 2007.</ref> The bill died in June 1974 but was reintroduced in the [[115th United States Congress]] on May 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://njtoday.net/2017/05/04/equality-act-reintroduced-congress-unprecedented-corporate-support/|title=Equality Act Reintroduced in Congress with Unprecedented Corporate Support|last=Report|first=Staff|date=2017-05-04|website=njtoday.net|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref>

In the early 1990s, supporters of the legislation decided to focus on employment. Rep. [[Gerry Studds]] introduced the Employment Non-Discrimination Act on June 23, 1994.<ref>[Congressional Record, 103rd Congress, 2d Session, 140 Cong. Rec. E 1311; Vol. 140 No. 81 (June 23, 1994).]</ref> The legislation failed in 1994 and 1995.<ref>Wendland, Joel. (April 9, 2007) [http://www.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/press/ANewBeginningforENDA.html A New Beginning for ENDA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125092049/http://www.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/press/ANewBeginningforENDA.html |date=January 25, 2008 }} The Williams Institute, UCLA School of Law. Accessed October 20, 2007.</ref> In 1996, the bill failed on a 49–50 vote in the Senate and was not voted on in the House.<ref>Bull, Chris. (May 13, 1997) [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1589/is_n733/ai_19736014 No ENDA in sight – Employment Non-Discrimination Act of 1996] The Advocate. Accessed October 20, 2007.</ref><ref>Manley, Roslyn. (June 17, 2003) [http://www.tgcrossroads.org/news/?aid=740 New "Unified" Bill to Replace ENDA: A Left Coast Perspective] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040217180400/http://www.tgcrossroads.org/news/?aid=740 |date=February 17, 2004 }} TG Crossroads. Accessed October 20, 2007; ''MetroWeekly'': [http://www.metroweekly.com/news/?ak=6567 Chris Geidner, "Double Defeat," September 15, 2011], accessed February 10, 2012</ref> Its level of support in the Senate may have represented an attempt by some to compensate for their recent support of the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] (DOMA), which prohibited the federal government from recognizing same-sex marriages.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} These early versions of ENDA did not include provisions to protect [[transgender]] people from discrimination<ref>{{USBill|110|HR|3685}}</ref> and ENDA was not introduced in the 109th Congress.

[[Image:United ENDA press conference.jpg|thumb|left|The "United ENDA" coalition protests the removal of gender identity from the 2007 bill at [[San Francisco City Hall]].]]

===110th Congress===

[[File:HR 3685 - Sexual Orientation Employment Nondiscrimination Act of 2007 (ENDA) - House of Representatives vote.svg|thumb|400px|right|House vote on '''Sexual Orientation Employment Nondiscrimination Act of 2007''' by congressional district.<ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/110-2007/h1057 H.R. 3685 (110th): Employment Non-Discrimination Act of 2007 (On Passage of the Bill)]</ref>
{{legend|#000080|Democratic aye}}
{{legend|#FF5050|Republican aye}}
{{legend|#C8C8C8|Abstention or no representative seated}}
{{legend|#5050FF|Democratic no}}
{{legend|#800000|Republican no}}]]

In the [[110th United States Congress]] there were two versions of the bill, both of which provided employment protections similar to Title VII of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref name=cra64>[http://finduslaw.com/civil_rights_act_of_1964_cra_title_vii_equal_employment_opportunities_42_us_code_chapter_21 Civil Rights Act of 1964]</ref> Reps. [[Barney Frank]], [[Chris Shays]], [[Tammy Baldwin]], and [[Deborah Pryce]] introduced {{USBill|110|H.R.|2015}} on April 24, 2007. It included [[gender identity]] within its protections. It defined gender identity as "gender-related identity, appearance, or mannerisms or other gender-related characteristics of an individual, with or without regard to the individual's designated sex at birth." It allowed employers to require adherence "to the same dress or grooming standards for the gender to which the employee has transitioned or is transitioning."<ref>Weiss, Jillian Todd. (April 26, 2007) [http://transworkplace.blogspot.com/2007/04/text-of-enda.html The text of ENDA] Transgender Workplace Diversity Blog. Accessed October 20, 2007.</ref>

When that bill died in committee, Frank introduced {{USBill|110|H.R.|3685}} on September 27, 2007, which did not include gender identity and contained exemptions concerning employer dress codes. It was endorsed by the Education and Labor Committee on October 18 and the House of Representatives passed it on November 7, 2007, by a vote of 235 to 184, with 14 members not voting.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2007/roll1057.xml Final Vote Results For HR 3685]</ref> Frank introduced a separate piece of legislation to prohibit discrimination in employment on the basis of gender identity.<ref>Eleveld, Kerry. (September 29, 2007) [http://www.advocate.com/article.aspx?id=41128 "ENDA to Be Separated Into Two Bills: Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity"] ''The Advocate''. Accessed October 20, 2007.</ref>

Some LGBT activist organizations refused to support H.R. 3685 because of its failure to cover gender identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetaskforce.org/activist_center/ENDA_oct1_letter |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509124722/http://www.thetaskforce.org/activist_center/ENDA_oct1_letter |archivedate=May 9, 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://nosubstitutes.org {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010191400/http://nosubstitutes.org/ |date=October 10, 2007 }}</ref> An exception was the [[Human Rights Campaign]], which received wide criticism from the LGBT community for supporting a non-inclusive ENDA.<ref>{{cite news |last=Schindler |first=Paul |date=October 4, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409024947/http://www.gaycitynews.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18883568&BRD=2729&PAG=461&dept_id=568864&rfi=6 |url=http://www.gaycitynews.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18883568&BRD=2729&PAG=461&dept_id=568864&rfi=6 |archivedate=April 9, 2008 |title=HRC Alone in Eschewing No-Compromise Stand |newspaper=Gay City News |accessdate=December 17, 2013}}</ref> The LGBT activist organizations that refused to support H.R. 3685 argued that not including transgender people undermined the underlying principle of ENDA.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Moment of Truth |first=Nadine |last=Smith |url=http://www.bilerico.com/2007/09/a_moment_of_truth.php |newspaper=The Bilerico Project |date=September 29, 2007 |accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref> They claimed that failure to include gender identity/expression weakened the protection for the portion of the LGBT population that most needed its protections: gender non-conforming people, who they claimed are discriminated against in greater numbers than their gender-conforming compatriots.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} Others argued that this was ENDA's best chance of passing Congress in thirty years, that civil rights victories have historically been incremental, that concerns about the legislation's protections were unfounded, and that forgoing a chance to provide immediate workplace protections to millions of lesbians, gays and bisexuals was politically and morally wrong.<ref>{{cite news |title=How did the T get in LGBT? |first=John |last=Aravosis |url=http://www.salon.com/2007/10/08/lgbt/singleton |newspaper=[[Salon.com]] |date=October 8, 2007 |accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref>

===111th Congress===
On June 24, 2009, Frank introduced {{USBill|111|H.R.|3017}} to ban workplace discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity,<ref name="advocate.com">[http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid93114.asp Frank Introduces Trans-Inclusive ENDA|News|Advocate.com:]</ref> with 114 original cosponsors, up from 62 cosponsors for the trans-inclusive bill of 2007."<ref name="advocate.com"/> The lead Republican cosponsor was Rep. [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] (R-FL).<ref name="wblade06-17">{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Chris |title=Pro-LGBT Republican endorses Romney |work=[[Washington Blade]] |date=November 30, 2011 |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2011/11/30/pro-lgbt-republican-endorses-romney/ |accessdate=June 25, 2009}}</ref> [[Republican Main Street Partnership]] members [[Mark Kirk]] (R-IL), [[Mike Castle]] (R-DE), [[Todd Russell Platts]] (R-PA), [[Judy Biggert]] (R-IL), and [[Leonard Lance]] (R-NJ) were among the original cosponsors.<ref>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d110:HR02015:@@@N Search Results – THOMAS (Library of Congress)]</ref> The bill was referred to the [[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|House Education and Labor Committee]], which held a hearing on the legislation on September 23, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bilerico.com/2009/09/congressional_hearing_on_enda_great_success.php |publisher=Bilerico.com |title=Congressional hearing on ENDA: great success!}}</ref> At the end of the 111th Congress, H.R. 3017 had 203 cosponsors in the House.<!--, on 3/3/10, 192 Democrats and 6 Republicans --><ref>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d111:HR03017:@@@P Search Results – THOMAS (Library of Congress):]</ref>

On August 5, 2009, Sen. [[Jeff Merkley]] introduced ENDA legislation ({{USBill|111|S.|1584}}) that included gender identity,<ref name=Thomas1584>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/D?d111:1:./temp/~bdZ4YW:@@@P|/bss/d111query.html Search Results – THOMAS (Library of Congress):]</ref> with 38 original cosponsors including Sens. [[Ted Kennedy]] (D-MA), [[Susan Collins]] (R-ME), [[Olympia Snowe]] (R-ME) and [[Chris Dodd]] (D-CT).<ref>{{cite web|title=Merkley, Collins, Kennedy, Snowe Introduce Legislation To End Workplace Discrimination, August 5, 2009|url=http://www.merkley.senate.gov/newsroom/press/release/?id=4EC04C19-3A3D-465A-A2A0-FA605C57AAAF|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> Sen. Merkley said "It's certainly possible that this could be passed by year's end, though the [congressional] schedule is very crowded."<ref name="Advocate08-05">{{cite news |last=Harmon |first=Andrew |title=ENDA Possible by Year's End |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=August 5, 2009 |url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid103460.asp |accessdate=August 5, 2009}} As Speaker of the Oregon House of Representatives, Merkley successfully managed the enactment of Oregon's state version of ENDA, the [[Oregon Equality Act]]. {{cite news |title=Senator Jeff Merkley Introduces the Employment Non-Discrimination Act (ENDA) |first=Kristin |last=Teigen |url=http://www.blueoregon.com/2009/08/senator-merkley-introduces-the-employment-nondiscrimination-act-enda/ |newspaper=BlueOregon |publisher=Mandate Media |date=August 5, 2009 |accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref> As of March 13, 2010, S. 1584 had 45 co-sponsors and was pending before the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions (HELP) Committee]],<ref name=Thomas1584 /> which held a hearing on the legislation on November 5, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://help.senate.gov/Hearings/2009_11_05/2009_11_05.html |publisher=U.S. Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions |title=Employment Non-Discrimination Act: Ensuring Opportunity for All Americans |work=Washington Blade |date=June 12, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103213535/http://help.senate.gov/Hearings/2009_11_05/2009_11_05.html |archivedate=November 3, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

===112th Congress===
On April 6, 2011, Frank introduced an ENDA bill ({{USBill|112|H.R.|1397}}) in the House to ban workplace discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity.<ref name="MetroWeekly 4-6-11">{{cite web|last=Geidner|first=Chris|title=ENDA Introduced – With 92 Fewer Co-Sponsors Than at the End of the 111th Congress|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2011/04/enda-introduced----with-92-few.html|work=MetroWeekly|accessdate=April 7, 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408023435/http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2011/04/enda-introduced----with-92-few.html|archivedate=April 8, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

On April 14, 2011, Sen. [[Jeff Merkley]] introduced an ENDA bill ({{USBill|112|S|811}}) in the Senate.<ref name="merkleypr112">{{cite web|publisher=Office of Senator [[Jeff Merkley]]|url=http://merkley.senate.gov/newsroom/press/release/?id=4CE98436-CD2B-445E-9E94-FCCF12B77C69|title=Merkley, Kirk, Harkin, Collins Introduce Legislation to End Workplace Discrimination|accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> The bill had 39 original cosponsors. On June 19, 2012, the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor & Pensions]] held a hearing on the bill, the first such hearing to include testimony by a transgender witness.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Chris|title=Trans advocate testifies before Senate on ENDA|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2012/06/12/trans-advocate-testifies-before-senate-on-enda/|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>

