===113th Congress===
{{wikisource|Employment Non-Discrimination Act of 2013 (H.R. 1755; 113th Congress)}}
On April 25, 2013, Representative [[Jared Polis]] (D-CO) introduced an ENDA bill in the House ({{USBill|113|H.R.|1755}}) and Senator [[Jeff Merkley]] (D-OR) introduced an ENDA bill in the Senate ({{USBill|113|S.|815}}).<ref>{{cite news|last=Benen|first=Steve|title=ENDA introduced with bipartisan backing|url=http://maddowblog.msnbc.com/_news/2013/04/25/17915739-enda-introduced-with-bipartisan-backing?lite|accessdate=April 25, 2013}}</ref>

On July 10, 2013, the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Health, Education, Labor & Pensions Committee]] approved ENDA by a 15–7 vote. Senator [[Lamar Alexander]] (R-TN) announced he would offer three amendments when the Senate takes up the measure.<ref name="Senate20130710">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2013/07/10/historic-senate-panel-advances-trans-inclusive-enda/|title=Senate panel advances trans-inclusive ENDA|date=July 10, 2013|publisher=Washington Blade}}</ref>

A [[cloture]] vote succeeded in the Senate on November 4, 2013, with 61 voting in favor and 30 against, allowing the Senate to schedule a vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2013/10/31/reid-sets-senate-vote-monday-enda/|title=Reid sets up Senate vote Monday for ENDA|publisher=Washington Blade|date=October 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/11/dean-heller-enda-legislation-99309.html|title=Gay rights advances in Senate |publisher=Politico|date=November 4, 2013}}</ref> Republican Senators [[Kelly Ayotte]] (NH), [[Susan Collins]] (ME), [[Orrin Hatch]] (UT), [[Dean Heller]] (NV), [[Mark Kirk]] (IL), [[Rob Portman]] (OH), and [[Pat Toomey]] (PA) voted for cloture,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/weigel/2013/11/04/enda_prevails_in_the_senate_61_30.html|title=ENDA Prevails in the Senate, 61-30|publisher=Slate|date=November 4, 2013}}</ref> joining 52 of 53 Democratic senators and both independent senators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=113&session=1&vote=00229|title=Roll Call Vote On Cloture on the Motion to Proceed (Motion to Invoke Cloture on the Motion to Proceed to S. 815)|website=www.senate.gov|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Senators [[Claire McCaskill]] (D-MO) and [[Lisa Murkowski]] (R-AK) supported the legislation, but were unable to attend the cloture vote.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/11/04/enda-vote_n_4214682.html|title=ENDA Vote: Senate Clears Major Hurdle On Bill Barring LGBT Workplace Discrimination|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=November 4, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/2013/11/04/breaking-senate-passes-enda-procedural-vote|title=Senate Passes ENDA on Procedural Vote|last=Brydum|first=Sunnivie|website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=November 4, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref>

After rejecting by a vote of 43–55 an amendment by Senator Toomey to expand the religious exemptions<ref name="Advocate-11-07">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/2013/11/07/breaking-senate-approves-enda-initial-vote|title=Senate Approves ENDA|last=Brydum|first=Sunnivie|website=The Advocate|date=November 7, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> and accepting by unanimous [[voice vote]] an amendment by Senator Portman to prevent government retaliation against religious institutions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/189434-senate-adopts-amendment-to-enda-aimed-at-protecting-churches|title=Senate adopts ENDA amendment designed to protect churches|last=Cox|first=Ramsey|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=November 6, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> the Senate approved ENDA on November 7, 2013, on a 64–32 vote.<ref name="2013 roll call">{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=113&session=1&vote=00232|title=Roll Call Vote On Passage of the Bill (S. 815 As Amended) |website=www.senate.gov|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/08/us/politics/senate-moves-to-final-vote-on-workplace-gay-bias-ban.html?hp|title=Senate Approves Ban on Antigay Bias in Workplace |last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 7, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Arizona Republicans [[Jeff Flake]] and [[John McCain]] unexpectedly<ref name="Advocate-11-07"/> joined Sen. Murkowski and the seven Republicans who had supported three days earlier. Both independents and 52 of 53 Democrats again supported the measure, with McCaskill present but Pennsylvania Senator [[Bob Casey, Jr.|Bob Casey]], who supported the bill's passage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.casey.senate.gov/newsroom/releases/casey-statement-on-senate-enda-vote|title=Casey Statement on Senate ENDA Vote|publisher=casey.senate.gov|date=November 7, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> absent.

In the House, on September 17, 2014, Representative Polis filed a [[discharge petition]], that, if signed by a majority of the House membership, would force a vote on the version of ENDA with a narrow religious exemption.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Chris|title=Discharge petition filed for ENDA with narrowed religious exemption |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/09/17/discharge-petition-filed-enda-narrowed-religious-exemption/ |accessdate=September 22, 2014|work=Washington Blade|date=September 17, 2014}}</ref> By September 22, it had been endorsed by 190 of the 218 that constitute a majority.<ref>U.S. House of Representatives [http://clerk.house.gov/113/lrc/pd/petitions/DisPet0011.xml Motion to Discharge a Committee from the Consideration of a Resolution], accessed September 22, 2014</ref> On December 3, 2014 6 of the 8 Republican co-sponsors asked House Speaker [[John Boehner]] to allow a vote on the legislation "as part of any available legislative vehicle including the [[National Defense Authorization Act]]" before the end of the 113th Congress.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow |first1=Justin |title=House Republicans urge Boehner to allow ENDA vote |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/12/house-republicans-urge-boehner-to-allow-enda-vote/|accessdate=December 3, 2014 |work=Metro Weekly|date=December 3, 2014}}</ref> Later that day, the [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]] voted 7 to 3 against adding ENDA as an amendment to the 2015 defense authorization bill.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=House panel rejects last-ditch effort to pass ENDA |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/12/03/house-panel-rejects-last-ditch-panel-pass-enda/|accessdate=December 3, 2014 |work=Washington Blade|date=December 3, 2014}}</ref>

===114th Congress onwards===
From the [[114th United States Congress|114th Congress]] onwards, efforts to pass non-discrimination legislation has focused on the broader [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]] which focuses on additional protections including in housing and the jury system as well as employment.

==Arguments==

===In favor of ENDA===
Political proponents of the law intend it to address cases where [[gay]], [[lesbian]], [[bisexual]], and [[transgender]] employees have been discriminated against by their employers because of their sexual orientation or gender identity. Currently, these employees are unable to find protection in the courts because sexual orientation is not considered to be a [[suspect class]] by the [[United States federal courts|federal courts]] and by many U.S. states. Proponents argue that such a law is appropriate in light of the [[United States Constitution]]'s guarantees of [[equal protection]] and [[due process]] to all. Advocates argue that homosexuality is not a "choice" but a personal identity, a claim supported by the [[American Psychology Association]] (APA), and that all working people have a right to be judged by the quality of their work performance and not by completely unrelated factors.<ref name= APA_ENDA>[http://www.apa.org/pi/lgbt/resources/employment-nondiscrimination.aspx# Examining the Employment Nondiscrimination Act (ENDA): The Scientists Perspective] American Psychological Association. Accessed May 22, 2010.</ref> According to a study published in 2001 by the Williams Institute at the UCLA School of Law, reports of discrimination based on sexual orientation are roughly equal to those on race or gender.<ref>Rubenstein, William B. (January 30, 2002) [http://www.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/programs/dogayrightslawsmatter.pdf Do Gay Rights Laws Matter?: An Empirical Assessment] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625003440/http://www.law.ucla.edu/WilliamsInstitute/programs/dogayrightslawsmatter.pdf |date=June 25, 2010 }} The Williams Institute, UCLA School of Law. Accessed October 20, 2007.</ref> The APA also states that there is significant discrimination against homosexuals in the workforce.<ref name= APA_ENDA/>

The Congressional Budget Office in 2002 estimated that the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]]'s complaint caseload would rise by 5 to 7% as a result of the proposed law.<ref>(April 24, 2002) [http://www.cbo.gov/showdoc.cfm?index=3527&amp;sequence=0 CBO Cost Estimate: S. 1284 Employment Non-Discrimination Act of 2002] Congressional Budget Office. Accessed October 20, 2007.</ref> Assessments of the impact of comparable state policies also show a minimal impact on caseload.<ref>{{cite web|title=Employment Discrimination against Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender People in Oklahoma|url=http://www3.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/publications/Policy-Discrimination-index.html|work=The Williams Institute|accessdate=May 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320004612/http://www2.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/publications/Policy-Discrimination-index.html|archive-date=March 20, 2011|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Regarding constitutionality, the act incorporates language similar to that of [[Title VII]] of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]],<ref name=cra64/> which has consistently been upheld by the courts.

In 1994, [[Barry Goldwater]], a hero among the [[conservative]] and [[libertarian]] movements, became honorary chairman of a drive to pass a federal law preventing job discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barry Goldwater, GOP Hero, Dies|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/daily/may98/goldwater30.htm|work=Washington Post|accessdate=November 2, 2013|date=June 5, 1998}}</ref>

===In opposition to ENDA===
Ed Vitagliano, director of research for the [[American Family Association]] (AFA), expressed concern about the impact of anti-discrimination laws on religious organizations. He cited a lack of clarity around whether the narrow exemption would apply to support staff and lay employees in addition to churches and clergy.<ref name="Vitagliano">{{cite web|last=Vitagliano|first=Ed|title=How ENDA Could Begin an Uncivil War|url=http://www.afajournal.org/0907ENDA.asp|work=American Family Association Journal|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>

The [[Traditional Values Coalition]] (TVC) has claimed that the legislation would have a negative impact on school children by eliminating schools' ability to avoid hiring transgender teachers. It said that "If ENDA passes, students and children in daycare centers all across the nation will be subjected to individuals experimenting with their gender identities."<ref>{{cite web|title=ENDA Hurts Kids: The Impact on Classrooms|url=http://traditionalvalues.org/data/sites/73/pdfs/_WPapers/070713_TVCELI_ENDA2013_FINAL.pdf|website=TVC Education & Legal Institute|publisher=Traditional Values Coalition|accessdate=July 7, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130223437/http://traditionalvalues.org/data/sites/73/pdfs/_WPapers/070713_TVCELI_ENDA2013_FINAL.pdf|archivedate=January 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

Some [[Libertarianism|Libertarians]] argue that laws against private sector discrimination are acts of [[coercion]] that infringe on employers' [[property rights]] and [[freedom of association]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Context Matters: A Better Libertarian Approach to Antidiscrimination Law|url=http://www.cato-unbound.org/2010/06/16/david-bernstein/context-matters-a-better-libertarian-approach-to-antidiscrimination-law/|work=Cato Unbound|accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>

The [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] said ENDA goes beyond prohibiting unjust discrimination and poses several problems. It notes, for example, that the bill: (1) lacks an exception for a "[[bona fide occupational qualification]]," which exists for every other category of discrimination under [[Civil Rights Act 1964#Title VII|Title VII of the Civil Rights Act]], except for race; (2) lacks a distinction between [[homosexuality|homosexual inclination]] and [[Same-sex relationship#Same-sex sexuality|conduct]], thus affirming and protecting extramarital sexual conduct; (3) supports the redefinition of marriage, as state-level laws like ENDA have been invoked in state court decisions finding marriage discriminatory or irrational; (4) rejects the biological basis of gender by defining "[[gender identity]]" as something people may choose at variance with their [[biological sex]]; and (5) threatens [[religious liberty]] by punishing as discrimination the religious or moral disapproval of same-sex sexual conduct, while protecting only some religious employers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Questions and Answers About the Employee Non-Discrimination Act|url=http://www.usccb.org/issues-and-action/human-life-and-dignity/labor-employment/upload/enda-backgrounder-2013.pdf|work=United States Conference of Catholic Bishops|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref>

In June and July 2014, several pro-LGBT advocacy groups, including the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], [[National Center for Lesbian Rights]], [[National Gay and Lesbian Task Force]], [[Transgender Law Center]], and [[Lambda Legal]], announced they were withdrawing support for the 113th Congress version of ENDA because of their concerns about the breadth of its religious exemption in relation to the ruling in ''[[Burwell v. Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.]]''.<ref name="MyUser_The_Huffington_Post_July_13_2015c">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/08/enda-religious-exemption_n_5568736.html |title=Gay Rights Groups Pull Support For ENDA Over Sweeping Religious Exemption |last1=Bendery |first1=Jennifer |newspaper=The Huffington Post |date= July 8, 2014 |accessdate= July 13, 2015}}</ref>

