A '''foreign national''' is any [[person]] who is not a national of the country in which he or she is residing or temporarily sojourning. For example, a foreign national in [[Canada]] is someone who is neither a Canadian citizen nor a permanent resident.<ref name="settler"/>
== In the United States == According to the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]], which is responsible for creating and [[wikt:revise#English|revising]] [[Law_of_the_United_States#Federal_law|U.S. federal law]], "the term 'foreign national' means. . . an [[Individual#In_law|individual]] who is not a [[citizen of the United States]] or a [[national of the United States]] (as defined in section [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1101#a_22 1101(a)(22)] of title 8) and who is not [[Permanent residence (United States)|lawfully admitted for permanent residence]], as defined by section [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1101#a_20 1101(a)(20)] of title 8."<ref>{{uscsub|52|30121|b}}</ref> In other words, U.S. citizens, U.S. nationals, and permanent U.S. residents are not foreign nationals when it comes to the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]] and the laws of the United States.<ref>{{uscsub|8|1101|a|3}}</ref> A permanent U.S. resident is statutorily entitled to U.S. nationality and at the same time strictly prohibited from spending more than six months outside the United States.<ref>''Rafeedie v. INS'', [https://casetext.com/case/rafeedie-v-ins-3#p522 880 F.2d 506], 522 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|D.C. Cir.]] 1989) ("See {{uscsub|8|1427|a}} (absence of less than six months deemed not to interrupt continuous residence for [[naturalization]] purposes)")</ref>
Any alien who is provided [[Temporary protected status|Temporary Protected Status]] (TPS), which is a special program that was created by the U.S. Congress in the early 1990s, is considered a foreign national. Unless shown by "clear and convincing evidence" to the contrary, such foreign national is not a [[refugee]] and has no right to U.S. nationality or permanent residency.<ref>''Saliba v. Att’y Gen.'', [https://casetext.com/case/saliba-v-attorney-gen-of-us 828 F.3d 182] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit|3d Cir.]] 2016); see also {{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/la-na-tps-revoked-20180720-story.html |title=The Trump administration wants more than 400,000 people to leave the U.S. Here’s who they are and why |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |editor=Melissa Etehad |date=July 19, 2018 |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref>
== In Canada == The law of Canada divides people into three major groups: citizens, permanent residents, and foreign nationals.<ref name="settler">https://www.settler.ca/english/?p=2259</ref> Under section 2 of the [[Immigration and Refugee Protection of Canada]] (IRPA), "foreign national means a person who is not a Canadian citizen or a permanent resident, and includes a stateless person."<ref>https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/laws/stat/sc-2001-c-27/latest/sc-2001-c-27.html?autocompleteStr=immigra&autocompletePos=1#sec2subsec1</ref>
==See also== * [[Alien (law)|Alien]] * [[Nationality]] * [[Immigration]] * [[Naturalization]] * [[Statelessness]] * [[Third Country National|Third country national]]
